Final Project

Today we’re going to walk you down the data science pipeline, mostly about how you can find certain historical events in data, but there’s also a fair amount of general exploration of data and how accessible data can be. In particular for this topic, I like talking about demography. Two of my favorite things in life are demography and staring at maps, and I feel like this project combines them quite nicely.

Step one is getting our data sets.

First we’re going to import some nice datasets, like the population by age range per year per country. This data spans from the years 1950 to projected populations in the year 2100.

We’re getting these first two datasets from https://esa.un.org/unpd/wpp/Download/Standard/Population/

All of the other ones are coming from the World Bank data set, https://data.worldbank.org. Search by the metrics listed. I can’t import these directly from the internet because they come with metadata CSVs in addition, and there’s issues with .zip files. The world bank in particular has an amazing data set.

Gee whiz, that’s a lot of data. This is what I love about R, it makes importing this data a simple 1 line command, wheras trying to do this sort of thing in Java, or (god help you), MySQL can be a real hassle.

This is a lot of good data, but it’s kinda ugly and it’s also not very normalized from a data base perspective. Each row has multiple data points(Per gender). There’s also a lot of redundant columns, so lets clean this up.

VarID and Variant are always the same thing, probably to differentiate this set from another data set, so those two can be removed.

AgeGRPSpan is always 5 unless it’s at the top of a range for a country for a year, so we can just change that to an “is final” range. This means that all the people in the top of an age group will be regarded as being in that 5 year range, but that isn’t very large anyway so this modification is pretty trivial. AgeGrp is always (AgeGrpStart,AgeGrpStart+4), so this column is also trivial.

Finally, we have these weird pop collumns, and it turns out it’s a lot easier in our later processing if we split these collumns into rows by gender. It triples our number of observations, but it makes our data a fair amount sleeker.

pyramid <- pyramid  %>% mutate(isFinal = ifelse(AgeGrpSpan==5,FALSE,TRUE))%>% select(-c(3,4,6,7,9)) %>% gather("Gender","PopCount",5:7) %>% mutate(Gender = substring(Gender,4))

We’ve cut our number of columns in half,but tripled our rows, but our data is looking a lot better. That index on the left is the ISO Numeric Code.

For some later processing, I’m pulling out a few special “countries”, which aren’t really countries, but income regions. I specifically exclude 1517(Middle Income Countries) because that is just a merger of 1501,1502.(Upper-Middle,Lower Middle)

But wait, what do these income regions mean?

Well, I searched more on that same site(Check under the “Other Files” tab), and I found another data set!

This one has a lot of location data, putting countries into certain continents, and listing certain special categories such as if the country is really smol or has an HIV epidemic. We’re going to basically only be using it for Income Level and Development Level data, although it has an important other attribute, which are the alphabetical and numeric codes. The numeric codes are useful because some countries like to call themselves different things, and the name of a country can be a politically sensitive topic(cough Former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia cough)

It also has the same country codes as in our other data set, which is really convenient for matching.

This data set, due to being an excel file, is really really dirty though. The first 15 rows are just a large title, and there’s all sorts of weird stuff going on with types and codes for regions and sub regions. Only of the collumns are labeled, because the command takes the first row for its names, and all of them are characters.

There’s all sorts of interesting zones that are listed, but aren’t really sovereign in this data, like the Island of Man, the Channel Islands, Sint Martin, and Greenland. We don’t care about them. There’s interesting information about certain countries being small, or having an ongoing aids epidemic, but we don’t need to know about that.

This is looking more usable. We cleaved off all that ugly whitespace at the top, gave ourselves some snazy names, and have a workable data set.

There’s a category for “less developed excluding least developed” countries, which I’m simply going to turn into our new less developed countries, so that these sets don’t overlap.

income <- incomecategories %>% select(c(2,4,5,12,14,15,16,18:20)) %>% filter(!is.na(HighIn))
cols <- c("HighIn","UMidIn","LowMidIn","LowIn","MoreD","LessD2","LeastD")
income[cols] <- lapply(income[cols],factor)

income$IncomeValue <- ifelse(income$HighIn == "Yes","High",ifelse(income$UMidIn == "Yes","Upper Middle",ifelse(income$LowMidIn =="Yes","Lower Middle","Lower")))

income$DevelopmentValue <- ifelse(income$MoreD== "Yes","More Developed",ifelse(income$LessD2 == "Yes","Less Developed","Least Developed"))
income <- income %>% select(c(1,2,3,11,12))
income$IncomeValue <- factor(income$IncomeValue,levels(factor(income$IncomeValue))[c(1,4,3,2)]) 
income$DevelopmentValue <- factor(income$DevelopmentValue)
income$LocID <- as.integer(income$`Country Code`)
income$`Country Code` <- NULL
head(income)

Now we filter out all the “NA’s” which tosses out most of the colonial remnants.

Next we really cut down on our data, and factorize it, because factors are generally easier to deal with than strings. Then we take the truth values of those factors because only one of the columns in each group should give us a yes. Now we have some really compact data, a list of each country by alpha code, income region and development region.

Visualization

Visualization is really fun, especially with a data set like this. Visualization is our next step after cleaning, because at this point we have an absurd amount of data that we can’t easily search around easily.

I searched around for a good plotting library for this data, because 216 entries is a lot.

Here are maps of our income and development regions!

The dividing lines here for income are a GNI per capita, or gross national income of ($1025, $4035, $12,467)

Clearly visible on the Income map is the European Union in 2004 and the Gulf Cooperation Council, those Arab Oil Barons. Most in the lower income category are also in the least developed category.

Visible on the development map is the so-called “North-South” divide, between Continental Europe, the Anglosphere, Japan, and the rest of the world.

Also, I included a quick table about the correlation between development and income. It isn’t as clear cut as one may think. Some countries have amazing income but are only moderately developed, like in the Persian Gulf. Ukraine and Moldova are well developed, but have below middling income, because they’re quite rural and suffered a lot from the braindrain and geopolitical shockwaves from the fall of the USSR. Belarus would have suffered as well, but Belarus is the last great dictatorship of Europe.

Now that we have our income regions well defined.

As a test of our data, we’re going to plot the data for the current year for each of these country groupings, in what is referred to as a population pyramid.

IncomePyramid <- pyramid%>% filter(LocID %in% LocationList$LocID, Time == 2018) %>% mutate(Location = factor(Location,levels=c("High-income countries","Upper-middle-income countries","Lower-middle-income countries","Low-income countries")))

MeanAges <- IncomePyramid%>% group_by(Location) %>% summarize(Mean= dot(AgeGrpStart+2.5,PopCount)/sum(PopCount))

#Can't even begin to tell you how much work it took to put this together
ggplot(IncomePyramid, aes(x=AgeGrpStart,fill=factor(Gender),labels=c("Age")))+geom_bar(data=IncomePyramid%>% filter(str_detect("Male",Gender)),aes(y=PopCount/1000),stat="identity") +geom_bar(data=IncomePyramid%>% filter(str_detect("Female",Gender)),aes(y=-PopCount/1000),stat="identity") +labs(fill="Gender",x="Age",y="Population(Millions)",color="")+coord_flip() + scale_y_continuous(labels=abs,breaks=(-8:8)*20)+ggtitle("Population Pyramid of countries grouped by income, 2018")+geom_vline(data=MeanAges,aes(xintercept=MeanAges$Mean,color="Mean Age"))+scale_x_continuous(limits=c(0,100),expand=c(0,0))+ facet_wrap(~Location,scales="free")

Aren’t these pretty graphs? The mean year is based on a rough average assuming each bracket is evenly distributed(It isn’t.)

High income countries are starting to age out, and will experience poulation decline in the upcoming decades. I There’s a visible scar in the upper escelons of the male population in high income countries, partially due to women having better life expectancy regardless of other factors, but also because of the massive casualties of the second world war.

Upper middle countries are starting to have their own thinning out as the result of better access to birth control.

Lower middle income countries take up the bulk of the world population, and have a very sustainable pyramid. Low income countries are low in number, but this is probably more of a reflection of the fact that they’re mostly in the most impovershed areas of subsaharan Africa and oceania. Here’s more visualization we can do!

PopData <- pyramid%>%filter(LocID %in%c(376,100,70,428), Gender=="Total" ,Time<=2018)%>% group_by(Time,Location) %>% summarize(YearPop = sum(PopCount))
ggplot(PopData,aes(x=Time,y=YearPop*1000,color=Location))+labs(x="Year",y="Population")+geom_line()

Here’s a quick aside about the fall of the iron curtain displayed with DATA. I’m not going to go terribly into correlations here, because the effect of the 90s is very apparent on the population of these countries, but I thought this would be a fun one.

We generate this graph by first filtering by location ID, “Total” gender, and year less than the current year(we don’t want their speculative data), then grouping by both time and location.

Bulgaria has been having issues since the collapse of the eastern block keeping its population stable, with more and more young bulgarians going to the nicer pastures of Germany and Western Europe.

Latvia is a depressed cold country that due to suicide rates, low birth rates, and emigration has fewer people than in 1950, and is the only country to have that trait.

Israel as a country is like… 1/3rd immirants, and has the highest birthrate in the developed world, at about 3.1 children per woman. You can see that slight additional uptick in the 1990’s after the fall of the iron curtain and thousands of Russian Jews moving to Israel.

Bosnia’s issue is this little geopolitical struggle known as the Yugoslav wars. Not a fun time.

The human population has over tripled over the past 60 years.

popGrowth <- pyramid%>% filter((Time==1950|Time==2018) &Gender=="Total") %>% group_by(Time,Location,LocID) %>% summarize(sumPop = sum(PopCount)) %>% spread(key = Time,value = sumPop)%>% ungroup()

popGrowth <- popGrowth %>% mutate(PercentGrowth = (`2018`/`1950`)**(1/68)-1) 
j<- joinCountryData2Map(popGrowth, joinCode = "UN",nameJoinColumn ='LocID')
## 194 codes from your data successfully matched countries in the map
## 47 codes from your data failed to match with a country code in the map
## 46 codes from the map weren't represented in your data
mapCountryData(j,nameColumnToPlot="PercentGrowth",colourPalette='terrain',mapTitle="Pop Growth(average % per year)")

popGrowthDevelopment <- as.tibble(merge(x=popGrowth,y=income,by="LocID")) %>% mutate(DevelopmentValue = factor(DevelopmentValue))
summary(lm(PercentGrowth~IncomeValue,data=popGrowthDevelopment))

Here, I take our old population pyramid, compare the 2018 population to the 1950 population using an an average exponential growth formula. Then we perform a linear regression to see if Percent growth is correlated with income value or development value.

We learn from this that there is a definite correlation between the birth rate and development at least between the least developed and the more developed countries. The P value for less developed gives us a usable p value at 5%, which isn’t that great, but certainly usable.

But I think the beauty of this map is that I didn’t even really need to do regression testing. We know which areas of the map are developed and undeveloped already, and the map just tells us what we want to know.

All in all the primary thing that I got out of all of this realtively noisy data, is that I could see the famine in North Korea simply from its crop yields. While the most agriculturally developed in the poorest section of the world, North Korea basically suffered agricultural collapse in the mid 90’s due to devestating floods that ruined North Korean electircal and agricultura infrastructure. They had to beg the international community for support at a great cost to their ideology of self-reliance.

Here we see that the top net emmigrating countries tend to be the most developed, witha few notable exceptions: Lebanon, Turkey, and Jordan have taken millions of refugeees from the number one net migrant country: Syria. Syria, despite being a country of about 20 million people, has seen over 4 million of its people flee a bloody multi-sided civil war.

The other top emmigrating countries tend to be some of the most populated ones on the planet, and the ones with the greatest population density in inhabited regions.

I guess what I’m trying to present as a message that we’re living in the most complicated time in human history, but we also collect enough data that we can get a good grasp on exactly how complicated it is, and maybe with enough eyes on the data we can pick out some patterns.
